                                                                                                               Promoters of Suzlon offload stake
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                               
	Mumbai, Sept. 23: Three promoters of Suzlon Energy today offloaded seven crore shares, which resulted in a sharp fall in the price of the scrip on the bourses.        
	In a filing before the BSE, the wind turbine maker said Nidhi T. Tanti, Brij J. Tanti and Girish R. Tanti  the promoters  had sold seven crore shares, or around 4.5 per cent of the companys equity.         
	The promoter group holding in the company has now come down to around 53.08 per cent.         
	The filing further said that these promoters intended to provide the funds raised through the stake sale to Suzlon either in the form of debt, or equity, subject to necessary approvals.        
	Speaking on behalf of the promoter group, Tulsi Tanti, chairman and managing director of Suzlon, said, The money is expected to be used for working capital and other funding requirements of the company.         
	Citigroup was the sole bookrunner for the transaction, which was targeted at institutional investors.         
	Though Suzlon did not disclose the money raised from the deal, it was understood to be around Rs 690 crore.         
	According to unconfirmed reports, the shares were sold at a discount to the scrips closing price yesterday. It is also believed that part of the proceeds would be used to retire debt.         
	However, the news of the share sale was not well received by investors.         
	On the BSE, Suzlon shares dropped 6 per cent to close at Rs 94.65.         
	After opening at Rs 98.40, the scrip rose to the days high of Rs 99.70 and, then, hit a low of Rs 94.                                                                                                                                                    
